atomic number}} 114. It is an extremely {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radioactivity"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
radioactive}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synthetic_element"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
synthetic element}}. The element is named after the Flerov Laboratory of Nuclear Reactions of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_Institute_for_Nuclear_Research"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Joint Institute for Nuclear Research}} in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dubna"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Dubna}}, Russia, where the element was discovered in 1998. The name of the laboratory, in turn, honours the Russian physicist {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgy_Flyorov"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Georgy Flyorov}} (\uc0\u1060 \u1083 \u1105 \u1088 \u1086 \u1074  in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyrillic_alphabet"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Cyrillic}}, hence the transliteration of "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yo_(Cyrillic)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
yo}}" to "e"). The name was adopted by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Union_of_Pure_and_Applied_Chemistry"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
IUPAC}} on 30 May 2012.\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
