In the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Periodic_table"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
periodic table}} of the elements, it is a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transactinide_element"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
transactinide element}} in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-block"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
p-block}}. It is a member of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Period_7_element"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
7th period}} and is the heaviest known member of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_group"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
carbon group}}. Initial chemical studies performed in 2007\'962008 indicated that flerovium was unexpectedly volatile for a group 14 element;\cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\super [10]\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\nosupersub  in preliminary results it even seemed to exhibit properties similar to those of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noble_gas"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
noble gases}}.\cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\super [11]\cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\nosupersub  More recent results show that flerovium's reaction with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
gold}} is similar to that of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Copernicium"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
copernicium}}, showing that it is a very {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volatility_(chemistry)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
volatile}} element that may even be {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gas"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
gaseous}} at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_temperature_and_pressure"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
standard temperature and pressure}}, that it would show {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metal"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
metallic}} properties, consistent with it being the heavier {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homology_(chemistry)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
homologue}} of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lead"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
lead}}, and that it would be the least reactive metal in group 14.\
\
About 90 atoms of flerovium have been observed: 58 were synthesized directly, and the rest were made from the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radioactive_decay"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
radioactive decay}} of heavier elements. All of these flerovium atoms have been shown to have {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_number"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
mass numbers}} from 284 to 289. The most stable known {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isotopes_of_flerovium"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
flerovium isotope}}, flerovium-289, has a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-life"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
half-life}} of around 2.6\'a0seconds, but it is possible that this isotope may have a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_isomer"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
nuclear isomer}} with a longer half-life of 66\'a0seconds; this would be one of the longest half-lives of any isotope of a superheavy element. Flerovium is predicted to be near the centre of the theorized {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Island_of_stability"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
island of stability}}, and it is expected that heavier flerovium isotopes, especially the possibly {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magic_number_(physics)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
doubly magic}} flerovium-298, may have even longer half-lives.\
